doc.ContractDescription: ELECTRICALLY DRIVEN LIQUID FILM BOILING A TWO PHASE HEAT TRANSPORT DEVICE DRIVEN BY ELECTRIC CONDUCTION MECHANISM IS AN INTERNATIONAL SPACE STATION EXPERIMENT TO INVESTIGATE THE EFFECTS OF GRAVITY ON ELECTRICALLY GENERATED TWO-PHASE FLOW AND ELECTRICALLY DRIVEN LIQUID FILM BOILING. THE PROPOSED WORK IS A COLLABORATIVE EFFORT BETWEEN THE INVESTIGATORS TO DEVELOP AND VALIDATE THE FLIGHT EXPERIMENT HARDWARE. WE PROPOSE THIS EFFORT BASED UPON THE SUCCESSES OF OUR CURRENT PROJECT, WHICH IS NASA GRANT COOPERATIVE AGREEMENT NNX12AR32G ELECTRICALLY DRIVEN LIQUID FILM BOILING A TWO PHASE HEAT TRANSPORT DEVICE DRIVEN BY ELECTRIC CONDUCTION MECHANISM. ALTHOUGH THE ORIGINAL EFFORT EXTENDS THROUGH FEBRUARY 2017, WE HAVE COMPLETED TASKS AND ACHIEVED THE TECHNICAL AND PROGRAMMATIC MILESTONES OF THIS PROJECT. THAT IS, WE HAVE PASSED ALL THE REQUIREMENTS OF THE SCIENCE CONCEPT REVIEW AND RECEIVED THE AUTHORIZATION TO ADVANCE TO THE NEXT STAGE OF THE EXPERIMENT DEVELOPMENT. THEREFORE, THE PI AND CO PI SUBMIT THIS PROPOSAL TO DEVELOP THE FLIGHT EXPERIMENT HARDWARE WITH AN EFFECTIVE START DATE OF OCTOBER 2016. THIS IS A PROPOSAL TO SUPPORT THE DEVELOPMENT OF THE EXPERIMENT FLIGHT HARDWARE FOR THE INTERNATIONAL SPACE STATION, CONDUCT THE EXPERIMENT ON BOARD THE INTERNATIONAL SPACE STATION, SUPPORT THE OPERATIONS OF THE EXPERIMENT AND EVALUATE THE EXPERIMENTAL DATA. THE PROPOSED PERIOD OF PERFORMANCE IS OCTOBER 2016 TO SEPTEMBER 2021. THE ROBUST COLLABORATION BETWEEN WORCESTER POLYTECHNIC INSTITUTE AND GODDARD SPACE FLIGHT CENTER CAN PROVIDE BOTH STATE OF THE ART THEORETICAL INVESTIGATION AND DELIVER FLIGHT QUALIFIED EXPERIMENTAL HARDWARE; THUS, THIS PROPOSAL PRESENTS BOTH INVESTIGATIVE AND HARDWARE DEVELOPMENT TASKS. THE PI WILL MAINTAIN OVERALL TECHNICAL DIRECTION OF THE EXPERIMENT DEVELOPMENT; HOWEVER, THE CO I WILL SUPPORT THE FLIGHT EXPERIMENTAL HARDWARE DEVELOPMENT IN COLLABORATION WITH GLENN RESEARCH CENTER.

doc.ContractDescription: SPACEFLIGHT EXPOSES CREWS TO UNUSUAL LIGHT-DARK AND WORK SCHEDULES THAT LEAD TO MISALIGNMENT OF THE CIRCADIAN PACEMAKER, RESULTING IN POOR SLEEP, IMPAIRED ALERTNESS AND INCREASED RISK OF FATIGUE-RELATED ACCIDENTS. SPACEFLIGHT IS ALSO ASSOCIATED WITH SHORT SLEEP (ONLY 6H/NIGHT) AND SO EVEN IN NON-SHIFTED SETTINGS, SUCH CHRONIC SLEEP DEFICIENCY WILL LEAD TO IMPAIRED PERFORMANCE. RECENTLY, WE AND OTHERS HAVE SHOWN THAT SHORT-WAVELENGTH (BLUE) LIGHT IS THE MOST EFFECTIVE WAVELENGTH FOR ENHANCING ALERTNESS AND PERFORMANCE DIRECTLY, AND FOR PHASE-SHIFTING THE CIRCADIAN PACEMAKER. LIGHT THEREFORE HAS THE POTENTIAL TO BE A SAFE, NON-PHARMACOLOGICAL COUNTERMEASURE TO REDUCE THE RISK OF PERFORMANCE DEFICITS AND CIRCADIAN MISALIGNMENT DURING SPACE FLIGHT. USING BLUE LIGHT ALONE, HOWEVER, IS UNDESIRABLE AS IT IMPAIRS VISUAL FUNCTION BUT MANIPULATION OF THE BLUE LIGHT CONTENT OF WHITE LIGHT HAS SIMILAR BENEFITS, AND CAN OPTIMIZE VISUAL AND NON-VISUAL LIGHT RESPONSES SIMULTANEOUSLY. NASA IS REPLACING THE CURRENT LIGHTING ABOARD THE INTERNATIONAL SPACE STATION WITH A NEW SOLID STATE LIGHTING ASSEMBLY (SSLA), INCORPORATING THREE PRE-DETERMINED SETTINGS TO ADDRESS DIFFERENT OPERATIONAL NEEDS: 1) WHITE LIGHT FOR GENERAL VISION; 2) BLUE-ENRICHED HIGH INTENSITY WHITE LIGHT TO ENHANCE ALERTNESS AND CIRCADIAN ADAPTATION; 3) BLUE-DEPLETED LOW INTENSITY WHITE LIGHT TO MINIMIZE ALERTNESS PRIOR TO SLEEP. WE HAVE DEVELOPED A DYNAMIC LIGHTING SCHEDULE (DLS) WHICH DETERMINES WHEN EACH OF THESE THREE SETTINGS WILL BE USED TO OPTIMIZE LIGHTING TO IMPROVE ALERTNESS AND PERFORMANCE, RESET CIRCADIAN RHYTHMS AND ENHANCE SLEEP, WHILE MAINTAINING VISION. LABORATORY-BASED ANALOG STUDIES OF THE DLS ARE ONGOING. THE CURRENT PROPOSAL WILL EXTEND THIS WORK TO APPLY THE DLS IN THE HUMAN EXPLORATION RESEARCH ANALOG(HERA) AS THE NEXT STEP IN EXAMINING THE FEASIBILITY AND EFFICACY OF THE SSLA SYSTEM, AND TO PROVIDE THE TESTING NECESSARY TO FINALIZE THE OPERATIONAL PROCEDURES FOR IN-FLIGHT TESTING OF THE NEW LIGHT ABOARD ISS IN 2016.
